Column references — the four ways.

PySpark accepts four different styles for naming a column. They are mostly interchangeable, but each one has a place where it shines.

The first is a plain string — just the column name in quotes. It works for the simple cases: select, group by, sort. It breaks the moment you want to build an expression, because a bare string cannot have a function applied to it.

The second is the col function, where you wrap the name in col. This is the safe default. It is what you use when building expressions, or passing a column into something like when, coalesce, or a sum. It does not really break anywhere.

The third is bracket indexing — the dataframe name followed by the column name in brackets. Its real job is disambiguation: when you join two dataframes that both have a column of the same name, this form says exactly which one you mean. It is just verbose for ordinary use.

The fourth is the expr function, which parses a sequel-style snippet of text. It shines when you want to paste in an expression like amount times point-zero-two. The catch is that it is just a string parsed at runtime, so a typo slips through until it runs. Rule of thumb: use a string when the interface only needs a name, col when you are building an expression, bracket indexing when you are joining, and expr sparingly.
